1
00:00:00,368 --> 00:00:19,068
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhu Dasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhu Dasa

2
00:00:19,640 --> 00:00:39,308
Namu Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:39,429 --> 00:00:45,798
So...

4
00:00:53,119 --> 00:00:54,161
I don't know how to stop that.

5
00:00:54,862 --> 00:00:55,963
That's the emails.

6
00:00:56,804 --> 00:01:03,173
So last week, last couple of talks, we covered Rupa.

7
00:01:03,874 --> 00:01:13,206
The first one was really about the sense bases, how the mind receives information, how it's then processed.

8
00:01:13,225 --> 00:01:14,587
And then the second one,

9
00:01:14,567 --> 00:01:22,117
which I should have done first, I suppose, was about the body as body as a contemplation object.

10
00:01:22,298 --> 00:01:32,691
So it was about movement, bringing mindfulness to movement, the cemetery contemplations, contemplating death and things like that.

11
00:01:33,572 --> 00:01:36,656
So now the next one is Vedana.

12
00:01:36,977 --> 00:01:41,722
So of the five aggregates, because that's what we're looking at, the five aggregates.

13
00:01:44,959 --> 00:01:50,588
And to start with Edna, we've got to go back to the point of contact, Pasa.

14
00:01:51,409 --> 00:01:59,423
So at Pasa, what we have is some information coming in at the sense bases.

15
00:01:59,862 --> 00:02:04,150
There has to be a sense base and then there has to be this consciousness.

16
00:02:04,811 --> 00:02:11,861
So it must arise on some sort of field, a screen upon which it can be known.

17
00:02:11,842 --> 00:02:13,724
So those are your three absolutes.

18
00:02:14,406 --> 00:02:27,002
And whatever comes in at that base is very minimal sensation, but it still comes under just about the idea of feeling.

19
00:02:27,965 --> 00:02:35,495
The distinction between that and feeling is that when it comes to feeling, it's defined as being pleasant or unpleasant.

20
00:02:36,417 --> 00:02:38,759
And the definitions get even more complicated.

21
00:02:39,229 --> 00:02:41,913
But at the point of passage, there's definitely a feeling.

22
00:02:42,354 --> 00:02:49,701
So some of them are very difficult to catch, like the feeling of photons on the retina.

23
00:02:49,782 --> 00:02:51,764
I'm not so sure that can be felt.

24
00:02:52,784 --> 00:03:01,936
But the fact that we can actually perceive light, that it's actually touching, is a sign that something must be being contacted.

25
00:03:03,497 --> 00:03:07,262
With the ear, it's a little bit better because at the...

26
00:03:07,866 --> 00:03:14,635
At the eardrum, you can actually experience the sound waves just as pressure.

27
00:03:14,975 --> 00:03:15,776
I mean, that's possible.

28
00:03:16,617 --> 00:03:22,344
And then you really know that there is a point where at the sense base, you're just getting raw data.

29
00:03:23,187 --> 00:03:27,512
And then the next thing is it takes it into the mind, the mind door.

30
00:03:27,830 --> 00:03:32,300
and it's at the mind door that we begin to perceive it differently.

31
00:03:33,644 --> 00:03:40,741
So this vedana feeling and perception, they arise together.

32
00:03:40,890 --> 00:03:46,356
I'll try and do a bit about perception, but I think there's a lot to be done here.

33
00:03:46,617 --> 00:03:47,399
So we'll see.

34
00:03:48,539 --> 00:03:57,330
And this point of contact is even there when it comes to the transcendental experiences.

35
00:03:57,430 --> 00:04:00,614
There must be some sort of contact that's known.

36
00:04:01,235 --> 00:04:06,561
And then after the experience, one reflects upon it, right?

37
00:04:06,710 --> 00:04:12,131
And those three contacts are, first of all, not self.

38
00:04:13,336 --> 00:04:16,348
So the contact of being empty of self.

39
00:04:16,817 --> 00:04:21,223
Ksumyata, empty of anything there at all.

40
00:04:21,843 --> 00:04:28,211
There's also what's known as the signless contact, which is basically that there's no impermanence.

41
00:04:29,312 --> 00:04:31,314
That's what they call it, signless.

42
00:04:31,394 --> 00:04:36,218
And then there's the freedom from desire.

43
00:04:36,620 --> 00:04:39,682
That's the one to do with dukkha, the suffering.

44
00:04:40,064 --> 00:04:45,930
So each one of these experiences which release us from delusion,

45
00:04:46,298 --> 00:04:53,947
also have this point of that point of knowing, that point of contact, you see, and then the rest is reflection.

46
00:04:57,971 --> 00:05:01,475
How important is that point of contact just in the order of daily life?

47
00:05:02,177 --> 00:05:10,185
Well, there was, I think I mentioned this before, for those of you who've listened to all my talks.

48
00:05:11,387 --> 00:05:12,829
Yes.

49
00:05:14,141 --> 00:05:40,250
when I when I used to go to work we used to we there were all these billboards and suddenly that appeared these adverts for an Australian perfume and it had a cork with a sort of Australian hat with corks of hanging around it you see and what had happened was that people with this modern advertising had lost faith in these billboards didn't think they're having much in effect

50
00:05:40,552 --> 00:05:50,422
But the amount of inquiries about this Australian perfume was such that, of course, they began to realise, in fact, it has an enormous effect.

51
00:05:50,922 --> 00:05:55,586
So just consider you're sitting on a bus and you're in a half dream.

52
00:05:55,627 --> 00:05:57,869
You're thinking about this, you're thinking about that and all that.

53
00:05:58,209 --> 00:06:01,954
But, of course, you avert, your eye catches this thing and it goes in.

54
00:06:02,314 --> 00:06:02,875
And that's it.

55
00:06:02,954 --> 00:06:03,694
It just goes in.

56
00:06:04,295 --> 00:06:06,338
And once it's in, you're conditioned.

57
00:06:06,577 --> 00:06:10,322
And the next minute, you know, you're craving for this Australian perfume.

58
00:06:11,432 --> 00:06:18,699
So that point of contact is the point of the beginning of conditioning.

59
00:06:21,702 --> 00:06:37,038
So that's why the Buddha says, this business of restraint, restraint of the senses, not to look at things that are going to build up old bad habits, to look at those things that are going to build up good habits.

60
00:06:37,858 --> 00:06:40,562
Well, that's one of the reasons for statuary and pictures, you see.

61
00:06:41,452 --> 00:06:46,480
As soon as you see, I mean, now, as you know, the Buddha statues become a sort of garden gnome.

62
00:06:47,081 --> 00:06:50,026
You can buy these things anywhere and stick them in your garden.

63
00:06:50,045 --> 00:06:51,569
Oh, there's a Buddha.

64
00:06:51,588 --> 00:07:03,045
So you can see it has people, even if they know nothing about Buddhism at all, they see in the statue some sort of expression of peacefulness, I presume, anyway.

65
00:07:04,788 --> 00:07:07,392
So that's how important that point of contact is.

66
00:07:08,572 --> 00:07:20,509
So now, this word veda, interestingly enough, is rooted in the word vid, which is similar to our idea of feel, when somebody says, oh, I feel it's wrong.

67
00:07:21,149 --> 00:07:29,262
So there's a feeling content, there's a sort of knowledge content with feeling, it arises, right?

68
00:07:29,281 --> 00:07:35,992
And that you could put down to knowing whether the feeling was wholesome or unwholesome.

69
00:07:36,192 --> 00:07:37,413
And you'll see later on,

70
00:07:37,394 --> 00:07:38,935
all sorts of other categories.

71
00:07:42,242 --> 00:07:52,096
Just as an aside, a writer does suggest that this split between the body and mind is a sort of Cartesian duality.

72
00:07:52,117 --> 00:07:54,761
You know, the mind is one thing and the body is something else.

73
00:07:55,963 --> 00:08:01,831
But they reckon it's a sort of spectrum of energy that moves from the physical energy into mental energy.

74
00:08:02,166 --> 00:08:04,288
And I dare say there's a truth in that.

75
00:08:04,769 --> 00:08:17,483
But there's also the mental body is actually has its own existence, as it were, which in traditional Buddhist understanding, when you die, that's what comes out, your mental body.

76
00:08:17,802 --> 00:08:20,865
And it's the mental body that then seeks rebirth.

77
00:08:20,886 --> 00:08:26,351
And if it hangs around where you actually died, that's your hungry ghost.

78
00:08:27,495 --> 00:08:51,241
yeah um i have no problem with that sort of understanding because even when i set up this place in london um a little meditation center we're trying to set up a meditation center there there was definitely somebody in the house and i could i could hear them moving about i could hear them rattling around and um at that time there was a friend of

79
00:08:51,457 --> 00:08:57,626
Actually, she was on the trust, Ramini, and she brought a friend along who was a medium.

80
00:08:58,368 --> 00:09:01,793
And we were just talking about this and that.

81
00:09:01,913 --> 00:09:07,181
And then I said, you know, I think there's somebody here who's hanging about.

82
00:09:07,240 --> 00:09:10,985
I said, because, you know, I got a feel for it and I can hear it.

83
00:09:10,966 --> 00:09:12,086
I can hear him.

84
00:09:12,206 --> 00:09:13,749
I didn't know whether it was a him or her.

85
00:09:14,009 --> 00:09:14,710
I just said him.

86
00:09:14,750 --> 00:09:15,571
I remember saying that.

87
00:09:16,211 --> 00:09:19,576
And she went into a silence, closed her eye and went into a silence.

88
00:09:20,116 --> 00:09:23,039
And it was about maybe three, four, five minutes.

89
00:09:23,080 --> 00:09:24,761
And when she came out, she said, it's all right.

90
00:09:25,383 --> 00:09:29,006
I've helped him find somewhere else to live.

91
00:09:29,027 --> 00:09:32,892
And from that time onwards, I didn't hear anything.

92
00:09:32,991 --> 00:09:33,793
And there were no mice.

93
00:09:34,974 --> 00:09:36,855
There was nobody.

94
00:09:36,875 --> 00:09:38,457
There was no dogs, no cats.

95
00:09:39,974 --> 00:09:40,674
So anyway.

96
00:09:47,384 --> 00:10:00,202
So the one thing that I think we need to ask ourselves is, when I seek happiness, what am I actually seeking?

97
00:10:01,745 --> 00:10:09,897
So, for instance, when I eat lovely food or see a film or have a romance and all that,

98
00:10:10,230 --> 00:10:16,499
There's obviously a base of things that I want, the food, the romance, etc, etc.

99
00:10:17,961 --> 00:10:25,811
But what is it that, for want of a better word, I really want from those experiences?

100
00:10:26,672 --> 00:10:28,394
What does I really want?

101
00:10:30,336 --> 00:10:36,985
Can I suggest that what we really want is a beautiful inner environment.

102
00:10:37,225 --> 00:10:38,888
We want to feel happy.

103
00:10:39,998 --> 00:10:47,570
We want actually an emotional state, a mental state in which we are happy.

104
00:10:49,712 --> 00:10:53,980
In other words, the food is secondary, the romance is secondary, everything's secondary.

105
00:10:54,461 --> 00:10:57,846
What I want to do is feel happy, not think happy.

106
00:10:57,865 --> 00:10:59,028
That doesn't get me anywhere, does it?

107
00:10:59,708 --> 00:11:05,197
And I can think, well, the word happy, it doesn't do much for me.

108
00:11:06,359 --> 00:11:08,081
But I want to feel happy.

109
00:11:11,216 --> 00:11:15,789
Am I getting regular nods at the back there?

110
00:11:15,809 --> 00:11:17,094
The four judges.

111
00:11:20,644 --> 00:11:22,470
Sitting on a high plane.

112
00:11:22,690 --> 00:11:23,251
Yes.

113
00:11:25,375 --> 00:11:32,686
So if we just take that for a moment, that actually all I want is to feel happy.

114
00:11:33,267 --> 00:11:45,063
And then, of course, I'm taught by society, et cetera, et cetera, culture and nurture and all that as to I'm brought up to believe that this type of food makes me happy, this type of music, this type of person, et cetera, et cetera.

115
00:11:45,745 --> 00:11:52,875
So I then begin to manipulate the world to try and really feel happy.

116
00:11:54,437 --> 00:11:54,538
Yeah.

117
00:11:56,121 --> 00:12:01,352
And in meditation, of course, that's what we're all yearning for, isn't it?

118
00:12:01,373 --> 00:12:10,873
The end of this continuous suffering and to just get blissed out for a moment or two and hopefully get into jhanas and stay there forever.

119
00:12:11,748 --> 00:12:22,863
So it's OK. Once we realize that, then then what it does is it it turns your attention towards the feeling content of your experience.

120
00:12:23,823 --> 00:12:24,163
You see.

121
00:12:24,424 --> 00:12:29,871
And then the question is, the question arises, is it worth it?

122
00:12:30,572 --> 00:12:31,254
Is it worth it?

123
00:12:31,494 --> 00:12:36,480
What I'm doing is the energy that I'm putting out there in order to get this inner feeling.

124
00:12:36,561 --> 00:12:37,501
Is that worth it?

125
00:12:37,684 --> 00:12:44,976
Now I'm being a bit cynical here because obviously there's a whole business of ethics involved, but we won't get into that just now.

126
00:12:48,643 --> 00:12:54,091
So it's the feeling tone of our existence, isn't it, as living beings, sentient beings.

127
00:12:55,293 --> 00:13:02,544
And the Buddha splits them all into different types.

128
00:13:02,692 --> 00:13:08,240
And so I just want to go through this particular discourse, which does that for us.

129
00:13:08,421 --> 00:13:10,104
It's called the Panchakanga Sutta.

130
00:13:11,525 --> 00:13:18,696
And Panchakanga was a carpenter and he went to Venerable Udayen and on arrival, having bowed down to him, sat to one side.

131
00:13:19,597 --> 00:13:20,558
He was sitting there.

132
00:13:20,759 --> 00:13:25,966
As he was sitting there, he said to Venerable Udayen, Venerable Sir, how many feelings has the Blessed One spoken of?

133
00:13:26,385 --> 00:13:33,053
Householder, the Blessed One, has spoken of three feelings, the feeling of pleasure, the feeling of pain, and the feeling of neither pleasure or pain.

134
00:13:33,575 --> 00:13:35,977
These are the three feelings that the Blessed One has spoken of.

135
00:13:36,678 --> 00:13:47,393
Now when this was said, Panchakhanda, the carpenter, said to Venerable Uday, the Blessed One has not spoken of three feelings, he's spoken of two feelings, a feeling of pleasure and a feeling of pain.

136
00:13:47,893 --> 00:13:54,942
And as for the feeling of neither pleasure nor pain, the Blessed One has spoken of it as a refined pleasure.

137
00:13:55,207 --> 00:14:04,038
The second time, Venerable Udayin said to Panchakanga the Khanda, the Blessed One has spoken of three feelings.

138
00:14:04,138 --> 00:14:13,288
And the second time, Panchakanga the Carpenter said to Udayin, no, the Buddha has not spoken of three feelings, but of two feelings.

139
00:14:13,308 --> 00:14:21,158
The third time, the Venerable Udayin said to Panchakanga, householder, the Blessed One has not spoken of two feelings.

140
00:14:21,177 --> 00:14:24,961
And the third time, Panchakanga said, no, the Blessed One has not spoken of two feelings.

141
00:14:26,461 --> 00:14:31,273
Now the Venerable Ananda overheard this discussion between Venerable Dayin and Panchakanta.

142
00:14:31,293 --> 00:14:35,384
So he went to the Blessed One and on arrival, having bowed to him, sat to one side.

143
00:14:35,443 --> 00:14:38,731
And as he was sitting there, he told the Blessed One the entire discussion.

144
00:14:39,100 --> 00:14:44,368
between a heck of a discussion.

145
00:14:44,388 --> 00:14:49,534
I'm not so sure it was a discussion, but it's often the way we sort of talk to each other.

146
00:14:49,554 --> 00:14:50,015
Yes, I am.

147
00:14:50,035 --> 00:14:50,456
No, I'm not.

148
00:14:50,475 --> 00:14:52,558
Yes, yes.

149
00:14:52,578 --> 00:14:54,381
And so venerable Andy.

150
00:14:54,721 --> 00:14:59,269
And then would not accept...

151
00:15:00,599 --> 00:15:15,283
Ananda, true was the exposition of Panchakanga the carpenter would not accept from Venerable Udayin and true was the exposition that Venerable Udayin would not accept from Panchakanga the carpenter.

152
00:15:16,426 --> 00:15:20,573
There is the exposition by which I've spoken of two feelings.

153
00:15:20,594 --> 00:15:21,375
So now he goes on.

154
00:15:21,625 --> 00:15:26,971
we actually get to 108, believe it or not, by the time it's finished.

155
00:15:27,010 --> 00:15:40,727
This is this whole business of deconstruction and trying to, through that deconstruction, trying to categorize different types of feelings so that we're clear as to what we want to develop in our own hearts.

156
00:15:41,969 --> 00:15:43,431
So the first two, of course, are

157
00:15:43,613 --> 00:15:51,486
A very simple split between pain and pleasure or what is unpleasant and what is pleasant.

158
00:15:51,506 --> 00:15:56,294
And in a sense, that at the base is the dual world we live in.

159
00:15:56,475 --> 00:15:57,517
You can't escape that.

160
00:15:58,057 --> 00:16:03,106
I mean, it's just part of our existence that we either feel happy or unhappy and so on.

161
00:16:04,048 --> 00:16:09,056
But then he goes a little bit more into categorizing.

162
00:16:09,076 --> 00:16:17,567
And then he's got the three feelings, which is dukkha, sukha, ka, means to bear, dumi is hard, sumi is easy.

163
00:16:17,706 --> 00:16:20,451
So hard to bear, easy to bear.

164
00:16:20,691 --> 00:16:24,336
And that which is neither easy to bear nor hard to bear.

165
00:16:24,923 --> 00:16:36,133
Now, the reason for that, of course, is to make us in our meditation become much more aware of these more subtle feelings that we tend to ignore.

166
00:16:36,854 --> 00:16:39,956
So we're usually aware of what's painful and what's pleasurable.

167
00:16:40,236 --> 00:16:46,022
But there's a whole set of feelings, neutral feelings that we're not particularly interested in.

168
00:16:46,883 --> 00:16:48,605
And it's just becoming aware of them.

169
00:16:49,024 --> 00:16:53,208
And of course, when there are no strong physical feelings,

170
00:16:53,797 --> 00:17:14,673
painful or pleasant feelings around then that's what you have you have that sort of pleasant neither pleasant nor unpleasant and of course the obvious one is the breath that's usually as long as there's no tension around the area that's usually very very neutral it's neither pleasant nor unpleasant

171
00:17:15,920 --> 00:17:23,991
And then he takes us just a little bit further and he talks about dukkha, sukha, domanassa, somanassa and adukkamassam.

172
00:17:25,114 --> 00:17:27,657
So this is trying to distinguish again.

173
00:17:27,758 --> 00:17:30,582
So he's always trying to deconstruct what we have.

174
00:17:31,063 --> 00:17:37,031
Those pleasures and pains that come from the body and the pleasure and pain has to do with the mind.

175
00:17:37,071 --> 00:17:40,877
So mental pleasures, mental happiness, happiness and unhappiness.

176
00:17:41,057 --> 00:17:45,183
So I suppose we would translate it as pain and pleasure.

177
00:17:45,586 --> 00:17:48,353
Happiness, unhappiness and neither.

178
00:17:48,894 --> 00:17:50,878
And that neither covers both types.

179
00:17:51,740 --> 00:17:52,844
So those are your three feelings.

180
00:17:52,884 --> 00:18:03,409
Now, again, it's the case of sort of in our meditation, just being aware that, you know, some feelings, some sensations are body based and some sensations are heart based.

181
00:18:03,540 --> 00:18:05,324
And again, that's that split.

182
00:18:05,344 --> 00:18:28,417
And of course, that does affect what we do in our meditation, because if it's something physical, we have to discern whether in fact it is truly just physical pain in the knee or something like that, or whether the physicality, the pain in the chest also has some sort of mental feeling involved in it, some sort of tension, whatever you say.

183
00:18:28,667 --> 00:18:39,800
And it's by investigating that that you might actually discover this separation where the physical feeling actually separates from the mental feeling.

184
00:18:40,402 --> 00:18:51,355
And of course, if you have that sort of experience, then the teacher becomes very clear to you that this mental feeling is causing this physical upset.

185
00:18:51,855 --> 00:18:56,320
And the physical pain or pleasure is like a sounding board.

186
00:18:57,001 --> 00:18:58,624
It makes everything louder.

187
00:18:59,413 --> 00:19:23,852
mental feelings are not so loud say that when they affect the body and then the body comes back as it were so anger is anger but when the body gets heated up and comes back with tension and ferociousness a ferocious sort of tightness then of course it makes it just that much more obvious to us yeah

188
00:19:27,005 --> 00:19:31,090
So that's the reason for sort of making that sort of distinction.

189
00:19:33,815 --> 00:19:38,161
Then there are the six feelings and they're based on your senses.

190
00:19:38,701 --> 00:19:42,086
Some of them are pretty straightforward, like hearing and smelling.

191
00:19:43,067 --> 00:19:45,049
Some are more subtle, you know, the eye.

192
00:19:46,231 --> 00:19:56,286
And then again, what comes in through the sense bases may have a physical base, but of course it's taken into the mind base.

193
00:19:56,451 --> 00:19:59,776
And that's when we determine it as being pleasant or unpleasant.

194
00:20:00,997 --> 00:20:04,842
So those are your six feelings.

195
00:20:04,882 --> 00:20:08,866
Then there are 18 feelings depending on the sense base.

196
00:20:09,567 --> 00:20:18,659
So each of these sense bases has an unpleasant and a pleasant and a neither pleasant nor unpleasant feeling.

197
00:20:19,038 --> 00:20:24,045
So you end up with 18 of different types of feelings.

198
00:20:25,307 --> 00:20:29,554
And the sixth one, don't forget the sixth one, which is, of course, the mind.

199
00:20:29,673 --> 00:20:35,241
So our experience of that we call emotions or feeling, emotions or moods.

200
00:20:35,602 --> 00:20:37,724
Even feeling covers that in our language.

201
00:20:39,186 --> 00:20:46,698
In the Buddha's language, there was this seemingly, was just this one word, vedana, which covered it all and had to be defined.

202
00:20:50,343 --> 00:20:54,268
And then finally, there are, so that leaves you with

203
00:20:55,395 --> 00:20:57,038
18, three types.

204
00:20:57,378 --> 00:20:58,381
Yeah, let me get that right.

205
00:20:58,961 --> 00:20:59,342
That's right.

206
00:20:59,702 --> 00:21:14,265
Then you can split them all again and get 36 different types of feelings, depending upon whether these feelings, physical, mental, etc., are worldly or non-worldly.

207
00:21:15,140 --> 00:21:27,194
Now that, of course, is an important thing because if you remember in one discourse, the Buddha says, one of the things he realized was that these thoughts were wholesome and these thoughts were unwholesome.

208
00:21:27,694 --> 00:21:30,778
And that if he followed the unwholesome thoughts, things got worse.

209
00:21:31,140 --> 00:21:33,342
And if he followed the wholesome thoughts, things got better.

210
00:21:33,663 --> 00:21:35,664
So this, in a sense, is at the feeling level.

211
00:21:39,288 --> 00:21:43,054
So these 18...

212
00:21:44,266 --> 00:21:52,419
are dependent on those three types of feelings multiplied by the six sense bases.

213
00:21:53,300 --> 00:21:54,903
And the sixth one is the mental one.

214
00:21:54,943 --> 00:21:57,748
So it includes all our emotional and mood life.

215
00:22:04,479 --> 00:22:07,944
He says, this is another discourse, this is what he actually says.

216
00:22:10,372 --> 00:22:16,180
Seeing a form via the eye, one explores a form that can act as a basis for happiness.

217
00:22:17,962 --> 00:22:21,327
One explores a form that can act as the basis for distress.

218
00:22:22,088 --> 00:22:25,513
One explores a form that can act as a basis for equanimity.

219
00:22:27,175 --> 00:22:30,019
And he goes through the different ones, the ear and so on.

220
00:22:30,099 --> 00:22:33,424
And then finally, cognising an idea via the intellect.

221
00:22:34,165 --> 00:22:38,251
One explores an idea that can act as a basis for happiness.

222
00:22:38,468 --> 00:22:41,832
One explores an idea that can act for the basis of distress.

223
00:22:42,512 --> 00:22:46,137
And one explores an idea that can act for the basis of equanimity.

224
00:22:47,220 --> 00:22:52,086
So that's one of the reasons why he split these into 18 different categories.

225
00:22:53,288 --> 00:23:01,597
It's what we do with the feeling that either makes it into something that's going to be wholesome or unwholesome.

226
00:23:03,800 --> 00:23:04,823
Yeah?

227
00:23:04,843 --> 00:23:05,083
Yeah?

228
00:23:10,008 --> 00:23:11,509
That's the 18.

229
00:23:12,931 --> 00:23:14,553
So yes, then...

230
00:23:19,657 --> 00:23:20,417
Yes, then...

231
00:23:21,219 --> 00:23:22,560
Sorry, I've gone back one there.

232
00:23:23,741 --> 00:23:24,542
There's all these numbers.

233
00:23:25,723 --> 00:23:36,654
So we can split these 18 again into what is wholesome and unwholesome, or as he would say, worldly and non-worldly.

234
00:23:37,296 --> 00:23:39,778
So now, if I can just read this...

235
00:23:43,588 --> 00:23:46,912
What are the six kinds of happiness?

236
00:23:48,894 --> 00:23:50,115
It's householder happiness.

237
00:23:50,134 --> 00:23:53,097
Here it's using the word householder, agarika.

238
00:23:54,019 --> 00:24:00,826
But the other word it uses would mean based on the flesh, based on sensual pleasure.

239
00:24:01,626 --> 00:24:10,035
Happiness that arises when one regards an acquisition, the acquisition of form cognizable by the eye,

240
00:24:10,436 --> 00:24:14,761
agreeable, pleasing, charming, endearing, connected with worldly baits.

241
00:24:17,584 --> 00:24:27,234
And when one recalls the previous acquisition of such forms after they have passed, ceased and changed, this is called householder happiness.

242
00:24:27,595 --> 00:24:34,561
So you've only got to think of times when you decide to go to a restaurant and you go through all the things that you might like.

243
00:24:34,582 --> 00:24:35,884
Is it going to be a curry?

244
00:24:35,903 --> 00:24:36,584
Is it Chinese?

245
00:24:36,944 --> 00:24:38,165
Are you going for a pizza?

246
00:24:39,698 --> 00:24:42,962
And you're reliving past experiences, right?

247
00:24:43,022 --> 00:24:48,431
Which is based upon our physicality, upon being a householder.

248
00:24:48,871 --> 00:24:50,093
However, we're renunciates.

249
00:24:50,834 --> 00:24:54,980
So what kind of six kinds of renunciation happiness?

250
00:24:55,760 --> 00:25:06,616
So the happiness that arises when experiencing the inconstancy of those forms, their change, fading and cessation, one sees with right discernment as it actually is,

251
00:25:06,917 --> 00:25:11,982
that all forms, past and present, are inconstant, stressful and subject to change.

252
00:25:12,303 --> 00:25:14,545
This is called renunciation happiness.

253
00:25:15,164 --> 00:25:23,432
So it's a case of, it's not that I think he's not saying that we shouldn't go to restaurants and have pizzas and all that.

254
00:25:23,732 --> 00:25:28,217
It's just recognising that the attachment to that is going to cause distress.

255
00:25:28,718 --> 00:25:36,924
But when we see that even pizzas come to an end, then we liberate ourselves from the possibility of terrible depression.

256
00:25:36,904 --> 00:25:43,173
And of course, that's the same for all the other senses, for sensations and ideas.

257
00:25:44,575 --> 00:25:45,715
So that's to do with happiness.

258
00:25:45,856 --> 00:25:47,097
So the similar formula.

259
00:25:47,979 --> 00:25:52,444
What are the six kinds of household distress?

260
00:25:53,066 --> 00:26:02,557
So the distress or unhappiness that arises when one regards as a non-acquisition, the non-acquisition of forms cognizable by the eye.

261
00:26:03,871 --> 00:26:07,674
The language gets a bit tortuous.

262
00:26:08,316 --> 00:26:11,919
Agreeable, pleasing, charming, endearing, connected with worldly baits.

263
00:26:11,980 --> 00:26:18,606
And when one recalls the previous non-acquisition of such forms, after they've passed, ceased and changed.

264
00:26:18,626 --> 00:26:20,489
This is called householder distress.

265
00:26:20,689 --> 00:26:24,172
So in other words, you wanted the pizza, but it wasn't open.

266
00:26:25,894 --> 00:26:28,237
So now you've got distress.

267
00:26:28,257 --> 00:26:31,380
So now you're going to have to have a Chinese, whether you like it or not.

268
00:26:31,849 --> 00:26:33,834
So that's what he's saying.

269
00:26:33,854 --> 00:26:36,940
If you don't get what you want, then you have this distress.

270
00:26:38,042 --> 00:26:46,338
So then he says, what are the six kinds of renunciation that cause this distress?

271
00:26:46,400 --> 00:26:53,554
The distress coming from the longing that arises in one who is filled with the longing for the unexcelled,

272
00:26:53,872 --> 00:27:12,854
when experiencing the inconstancy of these, of those very forms, their change, fading and cessation, he sees with right discernment, as it actually is, that all forms, past and present, are inconstant, stressful, subject to change, and he is filled with this longing.

273
00:27:13,535 --> 00:27:17,980
Oh, when will I enter and remain in the sphere of the noble ones?

274
00:27:18,621 --> 00:27:20,883
Now, enter and remain in.

275
00:27:21,423 --> 00:27:22,545
That's a strange, strange sentence.

276
00:27:22,846 --> 00:27:30,518
And when will I enter and remain in the sphere that the noble ones enter, are now in and remain in?

277
00:27:30,917 --> 00:27:43,538
So in other words, when we actually discern the distress that comes from not getting what we want, then there's this longing to become liberated, to be with the Buddha.

278
00:27:44,125 --> 00:27:53,545
And that longing, if it really takes us, it's known as a sanvega, which translates as an urgency, you know, a having to do it.

279
00:27:56,443 --> 00:28:01,250
So then the next one, of course, is what are the six kinds of householder equanimity?

280
00:28:01,310 --> 00:28:15,371
The equanimity that arises when a foolish, deluded person, a run of the mill, untaught person who's not conquered his limitations, all the results of actions and who is blind to danger, sees a form with the eye.

281
00:28:15,810 --> 00:28:18,434
Such equanimity does not go beyond the form.

282
00:28:18,938 --> 00:28:21,480
which is why it is called householder equanimity.

283
00:28:22,001 --> 00:28:25,244
So he's using the word equanimity, but it's a bit of a downer really, isn't it?

284
00:28:26,326 --> 00:28:35,356
It's the sort of feeling you get when you don't know the distress or the happiness you're in.

285
00:28:35,876 --> 00:28:38,681
You can't see where happiness is because you're too dull-minded.

286
00:28:39,020 --> 00:28:43,226
And even though you're in distress, you don't see yourself as being distressed.

287
00:28:43,946 --> 00:28:46,869
So people that say, I'm not angry,

288
00:28:47,743 --> 00:29:10,241
I'm not depressed so when you get that sort of deluded attitude which is driven by some wrong understanding then it's a sort of equanimity but obviously it's a poor equanimity I suppose our word would be indifference

289
00:29:11,048 --> 00:29:13,671
What's six kinds of renunciation equanimity?

290
00:29:14,251 --> 00:29:29,511
So the equanimity that arises when experiencing the inconstancy of the very forms, their change, fading and cessation, one sees with right discernment as it actually is that all forms, past and present, are inconstant, stressful, subject to change.

291
00:29:29,992 --> 00:29:31,875
This equanimity goes beyond form.

292
00:29:32,345 --> 00:29:35,891
which is why it's called renunciation equanimity.

293
00:29:35,911 --> 00:29:38,055
So spiritual renunciation equanimity.

294
00:29:38,555 --> 00:29:41,200
That's the equanimity when we accept the way things are.

295
00:29:41,740 --> 00:29:46,509
You know, things change, things pass, things die away, and so on and so forth.

296
00:29:46,528 --> 00:29:53,240
So that equanimity is to be discerned away from the equanimity that comes simply because we can't see.

297
00:29:53,740 --> 00:29:54,942
We're dull-minded equanimity.

298
00:29:58,011 --> 00:30:12,392
So, having explained the 36, if we then, through our memory, remember past times of those six particular types,

299
00:30:14,042 --> 00:30:20,310
So the six types.

300
00:30:21,031 --> 00:30:33,469
And if we then dream or think about future things, like now most of you, I'm sure, are dreaming of the amazingly wonderful things that will happen when you leave this place.

301
00:30:33,449 --> 00:30:37,056
And a sense of freedom and liberation that comes with it.

302
00:30:37,076 --> 00:30:47,917
So that sort of launching into the future, all that brings us now to 108 different feelings, which can either be pleasant, unpleasant, neutral.

303
00:30:48,298 --> 00:30:55,153
They can be worldly or unworldly, spiritual renunciation and all that sort of stuff.

304
00:31:00,584 --> 00:31:04,367
So that's how he split up all these feelings.

305
00:31:04,607 --> 00:31:09,291
He does say somewhere that people see feelings differently, categorize in different ways.

306
00:31:10,012 --> 00:31:17,941
But all the categorizations that the Buddha does is always to make us see more clearly where the point of delusion lies.

307
00:31:18,141 --> 00:31:22,345
So all these are about making us discern feelings.

308
00:31:22,924 --> 00:31:27,789
You know, first of all, from just this simple separation of pleasant and unpleasant.

309
00:31:27,769 --> 00:31:31,044
And then through to pleasant and neutral and so on and so forth.

310
00:31:31,787 --> 00:31:35,943
And how to discern what is good for us and what is not so good for us.

311
00:31:36,969 --> 00:31:38,032
To know what to do with it.

312
00:31:48,509 --> 00:31:51,913
Just another discourse, just to read it out.

313
00:31:52,895 --> 00:31:59,566
Thus have I taught the Dharma by means of exposition.

314
00:32:00,207 --> 00:32:11,664
When I've taught the Dharma by means of exposition, it can be expected that when there are those who do not consent to, assent to or accept what is well spoken and well stated by another,

315
00:32:11,644 --> 00:32:19,038
There will be arguing, quarrelling and disputing, and they will dwell wounding one another with the sword of the tongue.

316
00:32:19,818 --> 00:32:22,544
Thus have I taught the Dhamma by means of exposition.

317
00:32:23,766 --> 00:32:35,526
When I've taught the Dhamma by means of exposition, it is expected that when those who do consent, assent to and accept what is well said and well stated by another,

318
00:32:35,741 --> 00:32:44,976
They will live in harmony, with courtesy, without quarrelling, like milk mixed with water, regarding one another with friendly eyes.

319
00:32:46,838 --> 00:32:53,868
Obviously, it's a little reference to Udayin and Panchakango, seeming like these other's throats.

320
00:33:04,260 --> 00:33:20,582
Okay, there is a whole section then about the different types of refined feeling that come with concentration meditation and the eventual cessation of feeling and perception.

321
00:33:22,147 --> 00:33:32,410
So in the process of jhana, they're all beautiful.

322
00:33:32,569 --> 00:33:36,178
So there's no negative mental states or anything like that.

323
00:33:36,198 --> 00:33:42,351
But the first one, as you might know in our tradition, there's what we call the soft jhanas.

324
00:33:42,854 --> 00:33:49,534
for which there are seemingly, you know, scriptural support for that.

325
00:33:50,236 --> 00:33:54,990
And there are other types of jhana, which are deeper, which are known as the Visuddhi jhanas.

326
00:33:55,747 --> 00:33:58,509
written by Buddhaghosa.

327
00:33:59,270 --> 00:34:04,717
So that's a late text, about 700 years, I suppose, after the Buddha.

328
00:34:05,156 --> 00:34:10,402
But there are these two types of beautiful mental states that we can achieve.

329
00:34:11,423 --> 00:34:15,407
But they do have an agreement between them as to what the contents are.

330
00:34:16,309 --> 00:34:21,855
So the first one is that there is still some sort of mentation,

331
00:34:21,835 --> 00:34:36,750
even like the noting it can be as simple as the noting but the general feel is one of a physical joy a mental joy and then have I missed one out?

332
00:34:36,769 --> 00:34:40,853
and then equanimity is that right?

333
00:34:40,873 --> 00:34:51,184
yes before I've missed one out there's physical joy and there's mental joy oh dear

334
00:34:51,956 --> 00:34:52,521
I've lost it.

335
00:34:55,056 --> 00:34:55,721
And you ain't worried.

336
00:34:55,922 --> 00:34:56,989
I'm just trying to regain it.

337
00:34:57,880 --> 00:35:01,666
So you have the first two and then you drop one and you drop the other and then you go to equanimity.

338
00:35:01,686 --> 00:35:03,588
I think it's, yes, that's right, I think it's just the four.

339
00:35:03,909 --> 00:35:15,666
So on the first one, there is this mentation going on, but there's also a physical feeling of pleasure, a mental feeling of happiness, and behind it all is equanimity.

340
00:35:16,146 --> 00:35:22,757
And then as you go deeper and deeper, as it were, you move away from the mind, then from the body,

341
00:35:23,007 --> 00:35:28,099
And then from the happiness in the mind until you reach that state of equanimity.

342
00:35:29,141 --> 00:35:34,454
And from there, you can even go into what's known as the Arupajanas, where it's just pure equanimity.

343
00:35:35,155 --> 00:35:40,407
We're talking now about the feeling content of these mental states.

344
00:35:41,907 --> 00:35:51,998
There is a point where even the last of the Arupajanas, the ones that are not based on any material base.

345
00:35:52,018 --> 00:35:56,943
So, for instance, remember that when you start the jhana, you start on the breath and that becomes your base, you see.

346
00:35:56,963 --> 00:35:58,985
But with the Arupajana, there's no base.

347
00:35:59,045 --> 00:36:00,367
There's nothing there as such.

348
00:36:00,947 --> 00:36:04,472
So it says another pleasure, more extreme and refined.

349
00:36:04,822 --> 00:36:09,228
What, Ananda, is another pleasure more extreme and refined than that?

350
00:36:09,307 --> 00:36:16,036
What is the happiness which is even more refined than even these very refined jhana states?

351
00:36:16,056 --> 00:36:30,391
There is the case where a monk with the complete transcending of the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, so that's the last of these jhana states, enters and remains in the cessation of perception and feeling.

352
00:36:30,371 --> 00:36:34,896
This is another pleasure more extreme and refined than that one.

353
00:36:35,677 --> 00:36:45,927
Now it's possible, Ananda, that some wanderers of other persuasions might say, Gautama the contemplative speaks of the cessation of perception and feeling and yet describes it as a pleasure.

354
00:36:46,768 --> 00:36:47,369
What is this?

355
00:36:47,409 --> 00:36:48,250
How can this be?

356
00:36:48,309 --> 00:36:57,318
When they say that, they are to be told, it is not the case, friends, that the Blessed One describes only pleasant feeling as included under pleasure.

357
00:36:57,998 --> 00:36:59,721
Wherever pleasure is found,

358
00:37:00,123 --> 00:37:03,445
In whatever terms, the Blessed One describes it as pleasure.

359
00:37:03,885 --> 00:37:05,568
So it's the English here.

360
00:37:07,009 --> 00:37:08,409
He describes it as sukha.

361
00:37:08,471 --> 00:37:10,733
In other words, he describes it as happiness, right?

362
00:37:10,793 --> 00:37:12,793
So it's not physically based.

363
00:37:12,813 --> 00:37:25,525
So that's a state supposedly that can only be achieved by people who attain the third path and fruit, non-returner, the cessation of feeling and perception.

364
00:37:26,347 --> 00:37:30,130
And there is some dispute as to whether that is nibbana or not.

365
00:37:30,110 --> 00:37:32,733
But we won't worry about that.

366
00:37:33,554 --> 00:37:34,175
Just for the moment.

367
00:37:37,719 --> 00:37:38,179
Now let me see.

